{"type":"message","id":"73230d86","parentId":"89f045a1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:45:34.159Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_pyobxurd8ild_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 144415\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: state/goals.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine a concrete action.\r\n\r\nCurrent situation:\r\n- Phase 1 is complete with architecture cross-analysis and gap-decay synthesis\r\n- CFI compression experiment completed - showed CFI gives +32.9% precision but loses 92.9% recall\r\n- Key finding: constant-format tokens (freq=160, CFI=1) are metaprogramming artifacts with zero information content\r\n- Next pending action: Hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment (Strategy C)\r\n\r\nThe key insight is that I need to run the hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment. The formula is:\r\nscore(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120)\r\n\r\nThis should distinguish:\r\n- \"constant format\" tokens (freq≈160, CFI=1) → score = 1 × min(1, 160/120) = 1 × 1 = 1.0 (maxed out)\r\n- \"research trajectory\" tokens (freq<120, CFI>0.5) → variable score based on both\r\n\r\nWait, that's interesting - if freq > 120, min(1, freq/120) = 1, so constant format tokens (freq=160) would still score 1.0.\r\n\r\nLet me reconsider. The three-dimensional filter is: CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ≥ 3 AND freq < 120.\r\n\r\nFor the hybrid scoring:\r\n- Constant format: CFI=1.00, freq=160 → score = 1 × 1 = 1.0 (still high!)\r\n- Research trajectory: CFI=0.96, freq=136 → score = 0.96 × min(1, 136/120) = 0.96 × 1 = 0.96\r\n\r\nHmm, that's not distinguishing them well. Let me think about what the experiment should test.\r\n\r\n\r\nI need to refine the scoring formula to better differentiate tokens. The current approach doesn't effectively separate constant format and research trajectory tokens. I'll explore alternative scoring methods that more precisely capture the unique characteristics of different token types.\r\n\r\nThe scoring needs to penalize tokens with extremely high frequency while maintaining sensitivity to causal relevance. A logarithmic or inverse frequency component could help prevent constant format tokens from dominating the scoring mechanism.\r\n\r\nThe key insight is balancing frequency and causal inference importance without letting any single factor overwhelm the scoring system. I'm developing a nuanced approach that considers multiple token characteristics simultaneously.\r\n\r\nThe goal is creating a hybrid scoring method that distinguishes between different token types more effectively than current binary threshold techniques. By integrating CFI and frequency metrics, I can design a more sophisticated evaluation strategy that captures subtle variations in token significance.\r\n\r\nThe proposed hybrid formula introduces a frequency normalization step that caps the frequency contribution, preventing overly dominant tokens while maintaining meaningful signal differentiation. This approach provides a more balanced and granular token assessment mechanism.\r\n\r\nI'll develop a Python script to empirically validate the scoring approach, focusing on verifying whether the formula truly distinguishes between constant and research tokens. The key is ensuring the scoring method produces nuanced, meaningful distinctions across different token characteristics.\r\n\r\nThe script will leverage existing pulse_*.md files to systematically analyze token frequency and causal inference metrics, enabling a precise evaluation of the proposed scoring methodology.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI compression experiment revealed the \"constant format problem\" - tokens like \"for next instantiation\" (freq=160, CFI=1.00) are metaprogramming artifacts that appear in every pulse. The pending Hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment is the logical next step to test whether a multiplicative scoring formula can distinguish these zero-information tokens from true research trajectory tokens.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment script that tests Strategy C: score(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120). This experiment will validate whether this formula separates constant-format tokens from causal research tokens across 200 pulses with 80/20 split.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Hybrid CFI×Freq Scoring Experiment (Strategy C)\r\n**Date:** 2026-03-24  \r\n**Goal:** Test if score(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120) distinguishes constant-format from research tokens\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\n- **Constant format tokens** (freq≈160, CFI=1.00): score = 1.0 × 1.0 = 1.0 (maxed)\r\n- **Research trajectory tokens** (freq<120, CFI>0.5): score scales with both signals\r\n- **Problem:** Formula still gives max score to constant tokens. Need different approach.\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n- 200 pulses, 80/20 train/test split\r\n- Compare: Binary thresholds (CFI≥0.5 AND freq∈[3,120)) vs Hybrid scoring\r\n- Metrics: Precision, Recall, F1 on \"meaningful tokens\"\r\n\r\n## Analysis Script\r\nsee `scripts/hybrid_scoring_analysis.py`\r\nfile: research/HYBRID_CFI_FREQ_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 14:44:34\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774377934153}}
